A black box in your car?
While the planners of the U.S. road network have difficulty finding the money needed to repair the decrepit highway infrastructure, there are many who see a solution in the form of a small black box that is fixed above your car's dashboard.
The aircraft, which records every mile travelled by a motorist and transmits information to officials, is at the centre of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government planning offices to redesign the obsolete system of financing the major American roads.
The generally uninterested sector of the planning of the major axes has suddenly provoked a lively debate and a stirred alliance.
The libertarians joined ecologist groups to lobby for the government to use small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and possibly of the road you travel on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about the protection of privacy.
And while the members of Congress fail to agree on whether to continue, several States have not waited.
They are looking for how, over the next decade, they can move to a system that allows drivers to pay according to the number of miles travelled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS surveillance system, for an experimental shift.
This is really essential for our nation.
"It's not like we have a choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, Director General of the Southern California Association of Governments, which predicts that the state will start recording the miles travelled by every California driver by 2025.
There's going to be some change in how we pay those taxes.
The technology is there to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, financed with the taxes that Americans pay to the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to increase the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed trackers on 500 cars to test a payment system by mile.
"It turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long term," he said.
Wonks calls this from usage charges to mileage.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces urban liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California's planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the government's ambitious climate-warming laws.
But representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa), Chairman of the House of Representatives Transport Committee, said that he also considered it the most viable alternative in the long term.
Supporters of the free market of the Reason Foundation also appreciate the idea of paying drivers a mile.
"It's not just a tax going into a big black hole," said Adrian Moore, vice-president of politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they receive.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transport Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go along the road to payment by the mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved approximately 10,000 cars.
But the House Presidency killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who must travel many miles every day to their work or city.
However, several States and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country's most important experience.
These motorists will soon pay the state a kilometric fee instead of gas taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois tries a test on a limited number of trucks.
And coalition I-95, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the east coast of the United States (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) is studying how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where approximately 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their car with a device, drivers were concerned that the government would be able to follow their own actions and actions.
"The concerns about Big Brother and this kind of thing are a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, who leads strategic performance management in the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the beginning of the test, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site: "It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into fully located devices."
It is not necessary to build an enormous and cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily goings and comings.
Nevada is one of the few States that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the State to know how many miles a car travels, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to use a small California start-up called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to assist motorists who pay taxes to States.
She sought to break into the emerging auto insurance market, in which drivers would pay according to their mileage.
But the devices it tests have pleased the planners of the major axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't record their speed and locate them," said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are far less expensive means and far less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles travelled by all residents of the state.
Other States hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than enough.
In New York City, transport officials are seeking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide "pay-to-driving" insurance and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits offered by the system," said a paper on urban development.
However, some transport planners wonder whether the whole debate on mile payment is simply a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission of the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say that Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by increasing taxes on gasoline.
An additional single or annual tax could be imposed on hybrid vehicle drivers and others whose vehicles do not consume a lot of gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
"It's not necessary to resort to radical surgery when you just need aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, the director of legislation and public affairs at the commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a bunch of other things.
David Bowie: Four Unpublished Listeners
