Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that wounded soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was followed by all soldiers prior to their return to civilian life.
Attacked by Liberals and New Democrats in the House of Commons, Mr. Nicholson assured that before their release, members of the army were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
All wounded soldiers received appropriate care for their return to civilian life and none of them were released before they were ready, he said.
Detractors accuse the government of wanting to save money by not allowing injured members - who do not meet the "universality of service" rule of the army requiring staff to be able to perform a variety of tasks - to reach the 10-year eligibility period required for retirement benefits.
In particular, they cited two cases reported by La Presse Canadienne, including that of a soldier released last Friday.
Corporal David Hawkins, a reservist from London, Ontario, with post-traumatic stress syndrome, was released from the army despite his request to stay one more year in order to receive a fully indexed retirement.
His case occurred after that of Corporal Glen Kirkland, who told a parliamentary committee last month that he had been pushed out before he was ready because he did not meet the universal rule of service.
Mr. Hawkins emphasized that a soldier could be prepared from, with plans and consultation sessions, but that this was totally different from wanting to leave the ranks.
"I told them I wasn't ready," he said in an interview with The Canadian Press on Wednesday.
I asked for months if there was any way I could stay, and they said no.
Since the beginning of the major fighting in Afghanistan, the army has been struggling to determine what latitude it can give injured soldiers who want to remain in the ranks, but who are not capable of fighting.
Under current rules, seriously wounded soldiers have up to three years to recover.
If they do not meet the criteria for deployment abroad, they may be forced to leave the army.
Data presented to Parliament last year indicate that of the 1218 soldiers released for medical reasons, 199 had not reached the length of service required to obtain retirement benefits.
Liberal spokesman for veterans, Jim Karygiannis, called for the reintegration of Corporal Hawkins on Wednesday, while neo-Democratic Jack Harris called for the immediate end of "this shameful practice."
