Frontier Airlines plans to pay for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 to passengers carrying hand luggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for a hand luggage and $2 for a coffee or soda, although in its announcement Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could take the unopened can with them to the plane's descent.
The new cost of hand luggage concerns the bags stored in the upper compartment, so the small bags installed under the seat will always be free.
Frontier stated that it would pay $25 if the charges were paid in advance and $100 if the passengers only paid once at the boarding gate.
Border Spokesman Kate O'Malley indicated that the $100 was planned to encourage travellers to pay the fees in advance.
"We don't want to charge this price," she explained.
Airlines began charging first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to avoid these costs put as much as they could in the hand luggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no room in these compartments.
These costs are a way to ensure that passengers carry less things on board.
O'Malley stated that these new fees will not really be used to raise money.
It is a matter of making it clear to the most loyal customers of Frontier that it becomes increasingly difficult to find room in the upper compartments.
Passengers who buy their ticket on the airline's website will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger tailing a Frontier boarding gate could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the tail might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that the site and border registration procedures are changing to ensure that passengers know about these charges before arriving at the door.
Frontier's hand luggage costs will not be applied until the summer, although no dates have been set.
Passengers often rouse about baggage and other charges, but airlines love them.
They believe that the cost of handling baggage is significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street consider adding baggage charges as a sign that airlines pay enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of loss.
Yet many of them did not pay for luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. had applied the first hand luggage charges three years ago, and the low-cost Allegiant company followed a little later.
The only other company that imposes such charges is the Hungarian company Wizz Air, said the consultant with airlines Jay Sorensen, who closely follows the surcharge fees.
He estimated, in a December 2011 report, that Spirit's hand luggage costs were $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines manager, recently travelled on Spirit and wondered what he would find at the boarding gate when passengers discovered the unusual baggage charges imposed by the company.
"I've never seen such a fluid boarding process in my entire career," he said.
I was expecting to see teeth scratches and a fight burst at the door.
The aircraft was full, he added, "the passengers were on board at the speed of the lightning."
Frontier also acts as Spirit and applies $2 for coffee, tea, soda or fruit juice.
Frontier indicated that passengers who take soda or fruit juice can take the unopened can with them, and those who take coffee can be served free of charge.
It will always distribute water free of charge.
US Airways briefly attempted to charge for drinks in 2008 but returned back seven months later after the passengers complained and no other major airline had followed.
Frontier's decision to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not buy their ticket directly from the airline is his last effort to encourage customers to go to his site.
