Is the European elite ready to do business with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise to bring businesses together and define what wealth and job creators want to see change in our relationship with the EU.
To do so, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of UK business leaders and asked them what they thought about Britain, businesses and the EU.
YouGov interviewed over 1,000 entrepreneurs, broadly representative of all sizes of businesses, sectors and regions in Great Britain.
The findings of the survey will be a surprise to many.
We have discovered that the vast majority of companies are now seeking to export outside Europe, focusing on the countries that are modernising and developing while the EU states are stagnating.
They want to see the government give priority to new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil rather than becoming part of the long and arduous process of reforming the European institutional arenas.
When asked about specific policy issues – ranging from regulation of monopolies to product laws – most business leaders believe that control of these key competencies should return to Westminster's hands.
The single market has caused general discontent, with companies saying that the cost of the Brussels Regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European trade zone – 40% of the large companies, traditionally the most pro-European, even agree.
Finally, and more importantly, our corporate survey revealed that a large majority wanted Britain to continue its efforts to change the Treaty and develop a relationship with the EU based on trade and not politics.
This conclusion, which is found in all major groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the business world insists on a "significant change" that restores power to the United Kingdom.
