How biometrics will invade our lives
Finished the passwords to type to access his smartphone or pay for his purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future in which we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Deputy Director General of Morpho, even estimates that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person making transactions in a universe as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
The organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but they are concerned about it.
In 2011 and France alone, the National Commission on Informatics and Freedoms authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime," said Justin Brookman, responsible for consumer privacy at the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism in one, and pessimism in the other?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people who work concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection, as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand, presupposes a deliberate and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - we cannot capture this data without them - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
Consequently, research has been carried out over the last 20 years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to increased sensor accuracy and computer computing capacity required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, says Cyril Bataller, director of the Acence R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," says Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infallible marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers judicial police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognise one person among others) and authentication (make sure that the person is the person it claims to be).
The identification had so far concerned the issue of identity papers: the biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) must be compared with the information that the state has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not try to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance to a hotel or store.
"We collect the images of surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities who move freely on the Internet," says Dany Nassif, who is responsible for the commercial development of biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Other use: take a picture of a quidam who queues in a store, track its progression thanks to facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logic (opening of a computer).
More recently, the presence control was added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend who points for another," says Cyril Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the hit of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and major distribution signs: when paying in store with its bank card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger into a reader who scans the veins.
Experimentation is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at the French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that she can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in a box thirty seconds less, it's appreciable," explains the manager of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"Digital prints are stored on a first server; people's identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if you try to move it," says Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy experts continue to be concerned.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras, and the enormous amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me afraid of the worst: widespread surveillance," said Andrew Patrick, Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
