Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog's tail are related to his mood.
Previous studies had revealed that happy dogs moved more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs moved more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: "Everyone knows that in man, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was in other species.
He added that as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To find out more about how dogs react to the disorderly tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching films featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't take long before we understand why their tails sometimes go on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We presented to dogs films containing other dogs – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion – and we were able to traffic the tail movement and present it as going more left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression stir the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog that stirs the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail drifting mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog shaking the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not think that dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet several times with other dogs and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to that experience."
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine Behavior Expert John Bradshaw, visiting professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at Bristol University, stated that this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads left when they looked at an aggressive dog and right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "Dogs went more easily to a robot dog when their tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study."
He indicated that the differences could arise from the fact that dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of films or robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
"Although many elements, identified in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will certainly not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
