The cardinals are the highest church men placed in the Catholic Church behind the pope, and those who elect him, so François will appoint his first group of men who will ultimately choose his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, as soon as a cardinal reaches the age of 80, he can no longer participate in the election of a pope – it is therefore a group of 120 "electoral cardinals".
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a spokesman for the Vatican, said that a meeting bringing together all the existing cardinals would be held before the ceremony in which bishops will be raised to the dignity of cardinal, known as consistory.
"Pope François decided to communicate his decision to convene the February Consistory in advance in order to facilitate the planning of other meetings requiring the participation of cardinals from different parts of the world," Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of the Catholic Voices said that by February, the number of cardinal voters will likely have decreased.
He said that a pope usually named as many cardinals as it needed to have the number of cardinals voters reaching 120 and as many cardinals over 80 years of age as he wanted.
Next year's Consistory will be important because it will be the first since the election of Pope Francis in March this year, Valero said.
For the time being, there is a tendency to favour Europe and in particular Italy.
"It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he added.
40% of Roman Catholics live in South America, but a small number of cardinals represent them.
The cardinals will also be the first to be chosen since Francis formed the council of cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from all over the world to examine ways of reforming the church.
Previously, the pope decided on his own.
"Now, François chose these eight cardinals to help him," Valero explained.
He added that it was "very possible" that Francis asked the cardinals for advice.
But we have never experienced such a situation – it is totally new.
Valero indicated that the popes generally raised bishops representing vast communities as cardinals, but that François was "full of surprises – so we don't know who he will appoint".
GM recalls some of its new pickups in the U.S. to repair the seat folder
General Motors Co recalls nearly 19,000 of its all-new Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra 2014 pickups to resolve a problem with manually tiltable records, according to a Friday statement from the American vehicle safety regulator.
