"If the vehicle is hit by the rear, the head restraint may not properly protect passengers, thereby increasing the risk of injury," according to the statement posted on the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) website.
The models recalled were built between August 1 and September 10.
The deployment of GM pickups began in June and represents the most important vehicle launch for the first American automobile manufacturer since its bankruptcy and restructuring in 2009.
GM informed the owners of the fault pickups in the first half of October.
NHTSA was unable to review the letter of information to the owners due to the 16-day shutdown of government activities, which slowed the growth in vehicle sales in October.
Sales of Silverado and Sierra pickups, which were redesigned for the 2014 model, increased by about 20% in the first 10 months of the year, GM said on Friday.
In October, GM sold 42,660 Silverado pickups and 16,503 Sierra pickups.
GM stock price rose 1.4% to $37.47 at the New York Stock Exchange on Friday afternoon.
