A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society in New York identified a new species of bumper dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, responsible for scientific mission to the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Marines (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of bumpy dolphin surprise you?
That's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
If in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographic basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge of species classification sciences.
It is not impossible, moreover, that these advances in genetics and molecular biology call into question the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, family or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are called into question because of advances in genetics.
Similarly, two morphologically close species have been distinguished through genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
About ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific bumper dolphins and Atlantic bumper whales.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had been known to researchers for a long time, they did not know that it was part of a new species, only present there.
Therefore, if a problem of massive mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we may be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered on the basis of the number of individuals on Earth, that is, the stock, and the possibility that it will have to recover from neighbouring stocks.
With regard to the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the new species is discovered, its stock has automatically become smaller, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats where there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brewing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It is important to know that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, rather than knowing what lives in the Mariannas pit, only 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money in the search for life on other planets than in marine research and it's high time that this changes.
RBS suspends two traders in the foreign exchange market
Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange market division from two sources close to the file, showing once again that the global survey of regulators on the suspicion of manipulation of the foreign exchange market is beginning to bear fruit.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed that they are cooperating with regulators as part of the world's largest financial market investigations, where US$5.3 trillion change their hands every day.
The two traders are the first RBS employees to be suspended as part of the expansion of the investigation that echoes the scandal of manipulations of the interbank Libor rate.
The bank, which refused to comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it received requests for information from regulators.
"The ongoing investigation into this case is continuing and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and the other regulators," said a bank representative two weeks ago.
Last month, sources close to the file stated that RBS had transmitted instant emails and messages, sent to and by a former trader, to the UK regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and would have been suspended from his position as European cash trading manager for the currencies at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, European head of cash exchange trading at Citi, was released this week, while Matt Gardiner, senior foreign exchange trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders have been charged.
Mr. Usher's file included instant messages sent to and by bankers working at Barclays and Citigroup, adding sources close to the file.
UBS explained this week that it had brought an action against some of its employees after Swiss regulator Finma said it was investigating suspicions of foreign exchange market manipulations in a number of Swiss banks.
Around the world, at least six authorities – the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss Competition Authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority – are examining the allegations made about bankers who would have agreed to manipulate exchange rates.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Crédit Suisse also launched internal investigations or received requests for information from regulators, indicated sources close to the file.
Banks have been looking at instant messages and emails sent for years to find cases of wrongdoing.
The news of these surveys has shaken traders in a sector that has been one of the largest growth drivers of the trading units of investment banks in recent years, but which has been challenged this year due to the low volatility of currencies that limits the opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to minimize the case by saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the vast heavily liquid exchange market, but senior traders explain that this is not necessarily true.
One senior trader said that despite the high volume of daily foreign exchange transactions, the fragmentation of liquidity between trading management platforms and the increasingly frequent use by banks of their own internal platforms "explains that it is possible to start having an impact on the market at a low cost".
The news came the same day that Credit Suisse announced that it had returned a trader working in its office of funds traded on the London Stock Exchange this week after it caused a loss of $6 million at the end of last year.
The bank quickly informed the competent authorities and cooperated with the regulators.
"We are convinced that the trader acted alone and that the case was handled," said a representative of Crédit Suisse.
