Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopedias de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, art to tics and black ink to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, advances, of profile, fine as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, Henry Michaux's ink is projected.
The body, simple trait, takes shape.
And this form will be that of the whole piece: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, only the hands and face discovered, wait on each side of the play area, rush when the next graphic appears, embody it, emerge in current.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is made in relays of solos, in group to the unisson (a mass that makes solo), in large group of twelve solos where everyone executes his sign.
One thinks of "Glory of the morning", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on posters, placed online at the forestage.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, music is strong, percussions and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the rhythm is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, micro in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux's poem, monocord and monotone in the scream, and will continue by dancing.
And the music to leave, and the sequence to resume.
This loud and loud discharge, long, if possible, eventually stuns and numbs.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a force at Chouinard - like those hair that tumbles or those black fabrics that stretch the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, imposed himself, with his tics.
Result: The bodies seem flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux's inks, like Gestalt's shapes, open up a wider and more playful imagination than dance, more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers pierced by a stroboscopic light and the white signs in a suddenly black theatre, touches the magic.
The audience liked it, the reception was warm.
The Gymnopedias, after the entrance, are richer.
The scene is partly littered with grey, dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, such as furniture in a abandoned house.
At the piano, dancers are turning to play the scores.
Their bad addresses in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, they spend the couples, in love duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving sets, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffons appear, also familiar with Chouinard, with a red nose, in very polarized male-female love parades.
Loves are carnassiers, runaways or players.
Gestuelle, laughter and small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, grace and ridicule of the coitus, of the beings that merge.
But the room takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown comes back on stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes allowed: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes overlap, the cabotine dancers descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a wisely calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness pervade, and it is Chouinard's art, there, to contaminate the public.
