John Kerry admitted, unprecedentedly, that American espionage "had gone too far inappropriately"
John Kerry indicated that the defensive attitude of the United States towards its monitoring programs was softened by admitting, without precedent, that on several occasions espionage "had gone too far inappropriately."
The Secretary of State also admitted that he had, like Barack Obama, ruled on "automatic pilot" when a series of incendiary revelations by the denunciator Edward Snowden about NSA spying activities came to light.
The leaks put the U.S. government at the centre of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr. Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have become aware of certain things in automatic pilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course on September 11."
He then became the first senior member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed the line, but insisted that everyone's rights had not been violated.
He said: "In some cases, it went too far inappropriately."
And the President is determined to try to clarify and clarify clearly to people that he was now conducting an in-depth review of these practices so that no one feels wrong.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Mr. Kerry stressed, however, that the NSA was a force for good and that its monitoring operations had saved many lives.
He added: "We live in a new world where people are ready to jump."
There is radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and arrest them before they act?
We have prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding, and people from being killed because we were able to get to know the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. legislators will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. espionage case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint efforts to combat terrorism with the United States, said the president of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut indicated that he spoke to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made regarding the possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations because of the feeling of frustration caused by the surveillance of the National Security Agency.
"It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans remain with us in mutual engagement in the fight against terrorism," said Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chairman of the U.S. Senate's Subcommittee on European Affairs, during an interview from Washington.
And I am going to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger caused by NSA programmes.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has damaged relations with some US allies, but the Agency's director said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the United States.
Other revelations referred to documents released by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from the German Chancellor's mobile phone Angela Merkel and those of 34 other heads of state.
The Director of Intelligence, James Clapper, justified the spying of allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this tumultuous atmosphere, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a Congress trip this year, and he hoped that the delegation would include members of both parties and the two chambers.
The names of other participating legislators should be disclosed in the coming days.
He indicated that the route remained to be defined.
Murphy stated that the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show "affective firmness".
He explained that European Heads of State should be honest with their citizens about the type of espionage programmes they have been implementing for years.
"We can change our monitoring programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they also need to understand that we are not the only ones in the world to do espionage," Murphy said.
In the meantime, Mr. Kerry planned to visit the Middle East and Poland this weekend to manage the grudge generated by American strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as by United States surveillance activities.
